    <mj-section>
      <mj-column>
        <mj-image src="https://github.com/mjcampagna/mjml/blob/main/newsletters/202208-vol-03/Backlight-5-Protected-Photos-Hero-1200.jpg?raw=true" alt="Hero image; ." />
        <mj-text css-class="article">
          <p>Hi [Name,fallback=Friend],</p>
        </mj-text>        
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>

    <mj-section>
      <mj-column>
        <mj-text css-class="article">
          <h2>Updates</h2>
        </mj-text>        
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>

    <mj-section>
      <mj-column>
        <mj-text css-class="article">
          <h2>Stuff &amp; Things</h2>
          <p>Our curated list of recent, suggested listening, reading and viewing.</p>
          <dl>
            <dt><a href="https://techcrunch.com/2022/08/23/nerf-in-the-dark/">Google research AI image noise reduction is out of this world</a></dt>
            <dd>This demonstration of Google's "RawNeRF" neural radiance field A.I. is seriously impressive.</dd>
            
            <dt><a href="">Title</a></dt>
            <dd>...</dd>
            
            <dt><a href="https://youtu.be/Wnr4RJxDifw">The Story Behind Earthâ€™s Most Famous Photo</a></dt>
            <dd>New from PBS Digital Studios, <cite>The Bigger Picture with Vincent Brown</cite> delves deep into the history of a photograph, similarly to <a href="https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLJ8cMiYb3G5ce8J4P5j5qOEtYR94Z3DQs">Vox Darkroom</a>, which I've shared before. In this first episode, host Vincent Brown learns just how extraordinary a technical feat it was for Apollo 17 astronauts to snap the photograph in 1972, and how early environmentalists hoped that an image of the whole Earth might spark a desire to protect our planet.</dd>
            
            <dt><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N0bE6wYeqlo">How Cthulhu Transcended its Creator, H.P. Lovecraft</a></dt>
            <dd>Last newsletter, I shouted out <a href="https://www.youtube.com/c/pbsstoried">PBS Storied</a>. They've since released this episode about Cthulhu, and so I have to shout them out again, as I've long been a fan of Lovecraftian lore and stories (though, not so much his politics).</dd>
            <dd>As far back as I can recall, I got my start into the stuff as a child, playing Sierra's <cite>Quest for Glory</cite> series of point-and-click adventure games. The fourth in that series, <cite>Quest for Glory IV: Shadows of Darkness</cite>, weaved together Lovecraftian horror, Slavic folklore, and creators', Corey and Lori Ann Cole, signature humor into game that I remember very fondly to this day. It might also have been the first game I ever played with full (and hilarious) voice acting!</dd>
            <dd>Eventually, I read the stories themselves, and I actually have the very same edition of <cite>Necronomicon: The Best Weird Tales of H.P. Lovecraft</cite> sitting on my shelf that can be seen in the video.</dd>
            <dd>All these years later, the Internet and meme culture have transformed Cthulhu into a strange commodity, one that I cannot fully comprehend ... so very Lovecraftian ...</dd>
            
            <dt><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t1RTgznup5c">Music Pick: "The Call of Ktulu" by Metallica</a></dt>
            <dd>How could I not ... ? Had I never played the <cite>Quest for Glory</cite> games, I might never have recognized the reference in the song title when I eventually started listening to heavy metal. And <cite>Ride the Lightning</cite> remains my favorite Metallica album.</dd>
          </dl>
        </mj-text>        
      </mj-column>
